Dear Nick, could you please read the thread I wrote under this comment? Because there I explain why Holland is not the exact same as the Netherlands.

They cannot be combined under the greater name of Holland. Simply, the bureacratic system does not allow this. and, unless you have a map from before 1840, you cannot point out Holland on any map. You can point out  North-Holland and South-Holland and then wrongfully combine them in the here and now. And last but not least: Truth is not a democracy. Just because everybody calls the Netherlands Holland, doesn't make them right.

Yes there are a lot of people calling the Netherlands Holland. But this is the same as calling North- and South-Dakota just Dakota or North- and South-Carolina just Carolina. it is a wrong way of adressing a nation. And it can be very confusing once you go deeper into archives. And also:  North-Holland and South-Holland combined does NOT make Holland. Holland does NOT exist anymore since 1840. If you look at the Netherlands from a government point of view, those 2 provinces are VERY different

I am a homegrown Dutchie. I have just finished my disertation of my master of History on this very subject, the splitting of the great province of Holland. It is a common misconception that Holland means Hollowland. It really is a derived of the diets (!) prhase for woodlands, which is Holzland. This is new information, just dug up from the archives.
